<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
When you use another person&#8217;s ideas or words in your writing, include the editor(s) names and any relevant page number(s), in parentheses, immediately following the cited material. There is no need to include the abbreviation ed or eds.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Smith 25&#45;26).
</blockquote>
<br>
Or include the editor&#8217;s name(s) in your sentence, with the relevant page number(s) in parentheses.<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith suggests that &#34;the default position is markedly affected&#34; (23).
</blockquote>
<br>
When the editor is referred to more than once in the same paragraph only the page number is needed for subsequent citations, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Smith 25&#45;26). In addition&hellip; was a common feature (28).
</blockquote>
